{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471821"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:52:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:52:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"874"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/874"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.16,0.59,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47671"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/874"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32398"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"564"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2868"},{"type":"tags","id":"4068"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8319"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43042"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44034"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47671"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to her General Practice clinic with her mother as she is concerned that her daughter\u0027s periods have not yet started. She has a medical history of Turner syndrome, diagnosed at age 10. Her medications include thyroxine for hypothyroidism. On examination, she appears well. Her height is 140 cm (\u0026lt;3rd percentile) and weight is 45 kg. She has no breast development. Examination is otherwise unremarkable apart from some webbing of her neck.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassure and advise to await spontaneous menarche","Refer for growth hormone therapy","Refer for oestrogen replacement therapy","Refer for testosterone replacement therapy","Refer for progesterone replacement therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has Turner syndrome, a condition caused by complete or partial absence of one X chromosome. Turner syndrome is associated with hypergonadotropic hypogonadism due to ovarian dysgenesis and as such require \u003Cstrong\u003Eoestrogen replacement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E to induce puberty and maintain secondary sexual characteristics. In this patient with no signs of spontaneous puberty by age 14, oestrogen therapy should be commenced. Treatment typically begins with a low dose of oral or transdermal oestradiol, with gradual dose increases over 2-3 years to allow for normal breast and uterine development. After 2 years or once breakthrough bleeding occurs, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogesterone\u003C/strong\u003E is added to allow for withdrawal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough most girls with Turner syndrome will not undergo spontaneous puberty or menstruation, a small proportion may have some residual ovarian function. However, in this patient with an existing diagnosis of Turner syndrome presenting at age 14 with no signs of puberty, it would not be appropriate to simply \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassure and await spontaneous menarche.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is often used in Turner syndrome to increase final adult height. However, this is typically commenced in early childhood. In this 14-year-old patient who has already reached a height of 140 cm, growth hormone therapy is unlikely to provide significant additional benefit. The focus at this stage should be on oestrogen replacement to induce puberty.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETestosterone\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in some patients desiring masculinisation, but would not be appropriate as the first-line option for pubertal induction in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oestrogen replacement therapy is required to induce puberty and maintain secondary sexual characteristics in patients with Turner syndrome.","Growth hormone therapy may be used to increase final adult height in patients with Turner syndrome."],"references":["Gasner A, Rehman A. Primary Amenorrhea. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554469/","Queremel Milani DA, Tadi P. Genetics, Chromosome Abnormalities. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557691/","Morgan T. Turner syndrome: diagnosis and management. Am Fam Physician. 2007 Aug 1;76(3):405-10. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2007/0801/p405.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32398"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"874"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32398"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-26T20:26:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T08:27:35+09:30"},"relation